    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix resource block allocation conflict in RRC connection handling\n\n### Summary\nThe RRC connection handling code in eNB had a resource allocation conflict when processing UEs with duplicate random identity values. The issue occurred when a new UE connected with a random value that matched an existing zombie UE context.\n\nPreviously, the code would only mark the existing UE for removal by setting a timer, but would then attempt to create a new UE context with the same RNTI. This caused `rrc_eNB_get_next_free_ue_context()` to fail because the conflicting UE context still existed in the RB tree, leading to incorrect resource block allocation downstream.\n\nThe fix ensures zombie UEs are immediately removed from both MAC/PHY layer and RRC context tree before attempting to create the new UE context.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair2/RRC/LTE/rrc_eNB.c`: Modified `rrc_eNB_decode_ccch` to immediately remove zombie UEs when detected during random value matching\n- Added proper cleanup calls to `rrc_mac_remove_ue()` and `rrc_eNB_remove_ue_context()` before new context allocation\n\n### Reproduction\nUnder high UE connection load with frequent RRC connection requests, some UEs would fail to establish connections properly. MAC scheduler would report resource allocation conflicts and some UEs would experience connection timeouts. Error logs showed \"Cannot create new UE context, already exist\" messages.\n\nThe issue was more prevalent when UEs rapidly disconnected and reconnected, causing the random identity value reuse scenario.\n"
}